{meta: artist Dorsey M. Dixon}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[G]I used to be a factory hand [C]when things were moving [G]slow
[A7]When children worked in cotton mills each morning had [D7]to go
[G]Every morning just at five the [C]whistle blew on [G]time
[D7]And called them babies out of bed at the age of eight and [G]nine
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
[C]Come out of bed little sleepy head and get your bite to [G]eat
[D7]The factory whistle's calling you there's no more time to [G]sleep
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
[C]The children all grew up unlearned they never went to [G]school
[A7]They never learned to read and write but learned to spin and [D7]spool
[G]Every time I close my eyes I see [C]that picture [G]still
[D7]When textile work was carried on with babies in the [G]mill
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
[C]To their jobs those little ones was strictly forced to [G]go
[A7]Those babies had to be on time through rain and sleet and [D7]snow
[G]Many times when things went wrong their [C]bosses often [G]frowned
[D7]Many times those little ones was kicked and shoved [G]around
{end_of_verse}

